Weekly Summary of Cholera, Diarrhea and Dysentery Reports
---------------------------------------------------------
Date: Mon, 25 Jan 1999 09:03:53 -0600
Compiled by: Clyde Markon <docmarkon@worldnet.att.net>

[1
Mozambique (update)
Source: WHO Outbreak page January 19, 1999
Mozambique, where cholera is endemic, has been suffering an ongoing
epidemic since August 1997. At the end of July 1998, the total number of
cases officially reported to WHO was 26,738 with 619 deaths. The northern
provinces of Cabo Delgabo and Nampula, Niassa, Tete and Zambezia reported
cholera cases. At mid-December 1998, the cumulative figures were 34,621
cases and 985 deaths. The disease has spread rapidly to several districts,
and the situation remains critical.
[2
Tanzania
Source: Agence France Presse English, 18 Jan 1999
Cholera has killed at least 63 people in the southwestern Tanzanian region
of Rukwa in the last three months, press reports said here Monday. Rukwa's
regional medical officer, Landoline Wella, was quoted as saying that 604
people reportedly contracted the disease of whom 63 had died in the last
three months. Wella said the disease broke out in Mpanda, Nkansi and
Sumbawanga districts between October last year and this month. He said
that the disease was spreading fast in the Lake Rukwa valley and that more
efforts were needed to bring it under control. [Rukwa region borders Zambia
and the war-torn Democratic Republic of Congo.
[3
Kenya
Source: WHO Outbreak page 21 Jan 1999
The Ministry of Health, Kenya, has informed WHO of an outbreak of cholera
in Nyanza, Eastern, Rift Valley and Nairobi Provinces which started on 27
December 1998. As of 19 January 1999 a total of 1,025 cases with 25 deaths
is estimated to have occurred. Kenya has been suffering from a major
cholera epidemic since mid-1997. The cumulative total number of cases
reported to WHO was 17,200 in 1997 and 22,432 in 1998 with 555 and 1,237
deaths respectively.
[4
Accra
Source: Agence France Presse English, 21 Jan 1999
A cholera outbreak in greater Accra has so far claimed 18 lives out of 165
cases reported since the beginning of January, a Ghanaian health ministry
official said Thursday. The official told AFP that the worst affected areas
were Chorkor, Ablekuma, Ashiedu Keteke and Okaikoi, suburbs of the capital.
[5
Sierra Leone
Source: Agence France Presse English Thu 21 Jan 1999
The first cases of cholera were reported Thursday in Sierra Leone's
capital, Freetown.
[6
Zambia
From: Pierre Bigras <pbigras@netrover.com>
Source: IRIN - Central and Eastern Africa <irininfo@ocha.unon.org> 21 Jan 1999
The Zambian health authorities on Thursday announced a cholera in
Chililabombwe and Ndola in the northern Copperbelt district near the border
of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).In the past week, the
government said, 60 cases had been reported in an outbreak in the Ndola
district which has already claimed four lives.
[7
